{{good article}}
[[File:Dali - Nadiroba (Hunting) 2013.png|alt=A black and white image of a woman from the waist up. She is facing left. She wears a bearskin cloak, a fur dress, heavy earrings, and several beaded necklaces. A braid of hair is visible under her left arm. She is holding a decorated bow with an arrow drawn, and there is a dagger in a scabbard, and a quiver full of arrows on her hip.|thumb|Dali as depicted in the December 2013 issue of the Georgian magazine ''Nadiroba''. Her characteristic braided hair is visible under her left arm.]]

'''Dali''' (also '''Daal''' or '''Dæl'''; {{Lang-ka|დალი}}) is a goddess who appears in the [[Georgian mythology|mythology]] of the [[Georgian people]] of the [[Caucasus]] region. She is particularly prominent in the stories of the [[Svans|Svan]] ethnic subgroup, but others such as the [[Mingrelians]] had similar figures considered equivalent to Dali. She is a [[List of hunting deities|hunting goddess]] who serves as the patron of wild mountain animals such as [[Capra (genus)|ibex]] and [[deer]]. Hunters who obeyed her numerous taboos would be assured of success in the hunt; conversely, she would harshly punish any who violated them. 

She was usually described as a beautiful nude woman with golden hair and glowing skin, although she sometimes [[Shapeshifting|took on the form]] of her favored animals, usually with some marking to differentiate her from the herd. She was said to reside in a cavern high in the mountains, where she kept watch over the hoofed game animals who live on the cliffs. Dali was styled with a variety of regional [[epithet]]s reflecting her different roles and associations.

Stories of the Svan people depict her taking human lovers and killing them out of jealousy, giving birth to sons such as the [[culture hero]] [[Amirani]], and later clashing with her rival [[Tetri Giorgi|Saint George]].{{efn|name=StGeorge|In Georgian, Saint George is known as Giorgi. In Svan he is called Jgëræg, also transliterated as Dzhgyrag.{{Sfn|Tuite|2004b|p=14}}{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1968|p=483}}}} Some myths depict her working alongside other forest deities, and she is sometimes accompanied by the legendary hunting dog [[Q'ursha]]. Later stories, developed after the rise of [[Christianity in Georgia (country)|Christianity in Georgia]], conflate Dali with an evil nature spirit called the ''[[al (folklore)|ali]]''.

Many authors have described parallels between Dali and stories from other [[mythology|mythologies]]. As a patron of the hunt associated with hoofed beasts, she has been compared with [[Artemis]] of [[Greek mythology]], a [[Scottish mythology|Scottish]] [[hag]] called the ''[[glaistig]]'', and the maiden who tames the [[unicorn]]. Her associations with gold, seduction, and the morning star have led scholars to draw connections with goddesses such as [[Aphrodite]] and [[Ishtar]], who have similar mythological themes.

Her story remains an important part of Georgian culture. Though most younger people treat her as a mythological figure, some older hunters still consider her to be a real figure that one might encounter deep in the forest.

== Depiction ==
[[File:VittfarneGeorgien 155.jpg|thumb|The [[Caucasus Mountains]] of Georgia, where Dali was said to live]]
[[File:Trialeti silver cup.JPG|thumb|Seated figure and procession on the front of the Trialeti Cup]]
Traditionally, Dali lived in a cavern high up in the mountains, far away from human settlements.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=260}} Some traditions specified her home was the distinctive [[Double summit|double-peaked]] mountain [[Ushba]], whose ice-covered south face was sometimes called ''Dalis panjara'', the Window of Dali.{{Sfn|Anderson|2004|p=311}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=184}} The cave's exact location varied; it could be on the side of a glacier, or at the summit of the mountain.{{Sfn|Camuri|1993|p=123}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=106}} Sometimes the entrance was concealed by a rock door which Dali opened and closed to hide her dwelling.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}} Rarely, Dali and her flock lived inside an enormous hollowed-out [[spruce tree]].{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=107}} As a rule, Dali never entered civilized spaces such as villages except on rare occasions, such as the funerals of her human lovers.{{sfn|Tuite|2006|p=11}}

Dali was usually described as a beautiful young woman with long braided hair.{{Sfn|Davidson|2002|p=15}} She was most often portrayed as nude, occasionally wearing [[gold]] [[jewellery]].{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|p=178}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=16}} Her skin was so white it was literally radiant.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}}{{Sfn|Camuri|1993|p=123}} Her beauty was extraordinary: "both irresistible and terrible," it could drive a man to madness if he even spoke to her.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} 

Dali's long hair was an important component of her mythology. Most stories depicted her hair as gold-colored; in some cases, it was actually made of gold, and shone like the sun.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=260}}{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=158}} Some stories depicted this gleaming aspect as actual flame, describing the goddess leaving "little tongues of flame" in her wake, although this is less prevalent.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=60}} In some tales, Dali used her supernaturally-strong hair to bind hunters who wronged her.{{sfn|Khidasheli|1982|p=133}}{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=159}} In one story, she used it to strangle a hunter who had stolen one of her hairs to string his [[Bow and arrow|hunting bow]].{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=159}} 

Although strong enough to string a bow with, her hair was not invulnerable; indeed, making use of Dali's hair to threaten, harm, or kill her was a recurring motif in stories about her.{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|p=178}} Multiple tales depict hunters grabbing or cutting Dali's hair in order to subdue and rape her.{{sfn|Kveselava|2002|p=167}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=85}} This tactic did not necessarily prevent the goddess from taking revenge at a later date. In a story about Dali's [[Mingrelians|Mingrelian]] equivalent, the goddess agrees to become a hunter's wife when he threatens to cut off her luxurious hair. Later, he grows tired of her endlessly washing and combing it, and hides her prized comb so she will stop. She destroys his family, killing one of his children and stealing another, and curses his entire line of descendants in revenge.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=231}}

Women could also use Dali's hair against her. A woman whose man had been away hunting too long might cut her own hair off, praying that God would cut Dali's hair in return, which would force the goddess to allow her husband to return home.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=28}} In one of the major Dali stories, a woman discovers her husband sleeping with Dali. She cuts Dali's hair off in a rage, either killing her or banishing her from the world.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|p=121}} In one unusual variation of the hair-cutting motif, a woman wishing to rid her son or her husband of Dali's influence sneaks up on the goddess while she is sleeping and washes her hair, sometimes in deer's milk rather than water. Dali is rendered so powerless, or so grateful, by this act that she becomes the woman's servant.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=114}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=155}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=213}} Her Mingrelian equivalent could be dismissed with a similar method, using milk from a black cow instead of deer's milk.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=155}}

It is not known if there are any surviving artistic depictions of Dali contemporaneous to her period of prominence. Folklorist [[Mikheil Chikovani]] considered the [[Trialeti Chalice]], a Georgian artifact from approximately the 2nd millenium [[BCE]], to depict a round dance in honor of Dali.{{sfn|Khardziani|2006|pp=206–207}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|pp=25–26}} Folklorist [[David Hunt (folklorist)|David Hunt]] also suggested the Chalice could be a depiction of a female mistress of beasts.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=82}}

== Etymology and epithets ==
[[File:Northeast Caucasian languages.png|thumb|upright=1.2|Approximate distribution of the branches of the Northeast Caucasian languages, including the [[Nakh languages]]]]
The etymology of Dali's name is not fully clear. Although many figures in Georgian mythology have origins in figures from the early [[Georgian Orthodox Church]], Dali is not among them.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}} It has been suggested that the name comes from the [[Georgian language|Georgian]] word ''dila'', meaning "morning", or the [[Ossetian language|Ossetian]] word ''dælimon'' meaning "demon", but these links are disputed.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}} Anthropologist [[Kevin Tuite]] has linked the name to the various words for "god" in the [[Nakh languages]], a group of languages in the [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian language]] family: "[[Chechen language|Chechen]] ''dēla'', [[Ingush language|Ingush]] ''dǣlə'', [[Bats language|Bats]] ''dalě''."{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}} These words can refer to [[Allah]] specifically, or can be used as a general term for pre-Islamic deities in the region.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=12}} It was characteristic for central Caucasian cultures to replace sacred words with substitutes; this [[lexical replacement]] was driven by [[taboo]]s against speaking the true words. Tuite believed that Dali might originally have had a Svan name that gradually became replaced by the Nakh term for "god" as a result of this process.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=14–15}}

Dali and her equivalents were also known by various [[epithet]]s reflecting their numerous mythological roles. The Svan called her "the Queen Dali".{{sfn|Khidasheli|1982|p=128}} Because she was said to live high in the mountains, she was sometimes referred to as "Dali of the Rocks".{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|p=178}} In the [[Racha]] and Kakheti regions she was called "the Mistress of Beasts" and the "Angel of the Crags".{{sfn|Khidasheli|1982|p=128}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=106}} The Mingrelians referred to their equivalent goddess as "the Queen of the Woods" or "the Sovereign of the Forest".{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}}{{sfn|Khidasheli|1982|p=128}}

== Primary motifs ==
[[File:Bushy Park - White deer (cropped).jpg|thumb|A white deer, one of Dali's preferred animal forms|alt=]]

=== Game animals and hunting ===
Dali's primary mythological role was that of the mistress and guardian of hoofed game animals of the mountain. She protected her charges, which included deer, ibex, wild sheep, and [[chamois]], just as a shepherd guards a flock.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=260}} Some stories portray her milking her animals.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=18}} She was responsible for granting favor or misfortune to hunters, punishing the greedy and ensuring there would always be enough game to go around.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=18}}  

Stories involving Dali often feature animals that have been marked in ways that identify them as special: either they are Dali's favorites among the herd, or they are the goddess herself in the form of an animal.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=86}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=17}} Examples of these special features include a purely white coat, unusual markings, or golden horns.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}}{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=86}} Dali could vary her size in both her animal and human forms. When she took the shape of her favored animals, they were often significantly larger or smaller than the usual animals of that kind.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=34}}{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=86}} She could also make her human form very small: in eastern Georgia, hunters would leave tiny pairs of shoes on the cliffs as an offering to her.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}}   

Several tales recorded by Georgian [[folklore studies|folklorist]] [[Elene Virsaladze]] reflect the deadly consequences for a hunter who wounded or killed one of Dali's marked beasts, or hunted too greedily. Two stories describe Dali cursing a hunter's family such that his sons, and later the hunter himself, died as a result. Another story describes Dali destroying the town of Nakvderi with an avalanche as revenge after a hunter wounded a ''tur'' marked by the goddess.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|pp=86–87}} In another story, a hunter killed a doe and its fawn, and was cursed by the herd's protector to never have any descendants of his own.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=31}}{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=157}}

One Svan story describes the consequences for three brothers who follow one of Dali's mountain goats up into the crags and attempt to shoot them. The first two brothers both miss the goat, and are attacked and killed by Dali, who has been hiding in her cave nearby watching. The third brother watches the goat vanish into Dali's cave, and hides. Dali eventually emerges. The hunter leaps out of hiding, grabs her by the hair, and rapes her. She then becomes his mistress.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|pp=83–84}} The story's unusual inclusion of a hunter who overpowers Dali may indicate that it took some influence from an [[Ossetians|Ossetian]] legend involving two brothers overcoming a deer-herding witch.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}}

=== Appeasement through taboos and offerings  ===
Despite her protectiveness towards her animals, Dali was not necessarily hostile to hunters, and would even grant them blessings if they respected certain [[taboo]]s and made appropriate offerings to her. These taboos typically revolved around concerns about [[Ritual purification|spiritual purity]] and prevention of [[Overexploitation|overhunting]].{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}} Offerings usually involved small personal [[sacrifice]]s given before and after the hunt.{{Sfn|Salia|1983|p=32}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}}

Dali was perceived as extremely sensitive to any kind of pollution entering her mountains, which were considered pure and therefore sacred.{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=6}}{{sfn|Tuite|2007|p=23}} She demanded that hunters abstain from the hunt if they were impure in any of a number of ways, usually relating to women and blood, but also associated with foul language, adulterous acts, and recent death.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2007|p=28}}{{Sfn|Tuite|1997|p=6}} On the night before a hunt, hunters had to refrain from intercourse with any women, even their wives.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} They had to avoid any contact, sexual or otherwise, with any woman who was in [[childbirth]] or [[Menstruation|menstruating]], as menstrual blood was seen to be impure (a form of [[menstrual taboo]]).{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}}{{Sfn|Bakker|2013|pp=83–84}} The wives of hunters were also subject to behavioral taboos. In some regions, "the wives of huntsmen were traditionally forbidden to wash, comb, or unplait their hair" while their husbands were out on the hunt.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=158}} In an extension of the hunter's menstrual taboo, women were not permitted to eat meat from the hunt while menstruating, pregnant, or in childbirth.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2007|p=28}}
[[File:E - Capra aegagrus aegagrus horns.jpg|thumb|Horns of the [[Bezoar ibex]], native to the Georgian mountains]]
Hunting was treated as a sacred act among the Svan. The hunt began with a sacrifice of a ceremonial bread, called ''lamsir'', which was offered to Dali with a prayer.{{Sfn|Salia|1983|p=32}} Hunters were taught not to kill more beasts than they could carry, usually one for each man in the hunting party.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}} If their efforts were successful, hunters would make an offering of organ meat to Dali in thanksgiving.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}} In some traditions, the horns of the animal would be consecrated to Dali once the hunters returned to their village.{{Sfn|Salia|1983|p=33}}

It was believed that hunters who respected these taboos and made correct offerings, thereby avoiding ritual impurity, would always find enough game to ensure that they and their families were fed.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=18}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2007|p=30}} Conversely, hunters who became impure by failing to abide by taboos and restrictions could be punished by Dali in a number of ways ranging from failure to find game all the way to death by fatal fall, depending on the severity of the violation.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=2}} It was sometimes possible to abate Dali's rage after a transgression with appropriate offerings, as in one story where an offering of sacred bread prevented Dali from destroying a village by flooding the [[Enguri River|Inguri River]].{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2007|p=79}}

=== Seduction and jealousy ===
[[File:Old peasant with dagger and long smoking pipe, Mestia, Svanetia, Georgia (Republic).Color.jpg|thumb|A Svaneti hunter in traditional garb]]
Stories involving Dali often depict her taking mortal hunters as lovers, bringing both blessings and peril to the hunter in question.{{Sfn|Bakker|2013|pp=83–84}}{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} In an inversion of traditional gender roles, it is the goddess who chooses the hunter and initiates the affair.{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=6}} Often, her target was a hunter who had done her a favor such as protecting her from a pursuer.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=33}} She would give her lovers tokens of affection such as beads, jewellery, or small objects like scissors, which he was required to keep hidden from everyone.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=65}} A hunter who became Dali's lover would be guaranteed success in the hunt.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} The goddess might even protect the hunter from human assailants and heal his wounds.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=206}} In return, he was prohibited from revealing the secret of his good fortune, and from taking any mortal lovers for the duration of the affair.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} 

Engaging in an affair with Dali was a dangerous undertaking. Dali's beauty would inflame the hunter's passions to the point of near-madness, a state that was referred to as being "''dalelukdune,'' Dali-possessed".{{Sfn|Salia|1983|p=33}} Afflicted hunters would wander the wilderness aimlessly waiting for the goddess to find them.{{Sfn|Salia|1983|p=33}} After the affair was consummated, any appearance of infidelity on the hunter's part could incur the goddess's fatal wrath. He could be attacked by her animals or lured to his death upon a dangerous cliff. Dali's Mingrelian equivalent was known to [[Petrifaction in mythology and fiction|petrify]] hunters who offended her.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}} Even if a hunter did survive the liaison, he might be unable to take a mortal lover for the remainder of his life for fear of angering the goddess.{{sfn|Davidson|2002|p=15}} 

It was possible for a wily hunter to negotiate terms with Dali, such as limiting the length of the affair, or securing the right to marry a mortal at a later time. As long as the hunter's terms were set before the affair began, Dali would respect them.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=34}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=239}} Some traditions held that a hunter could safely end an affair with Dali by giving his undergarments to a male guest, who would become the new focus of Dali's affections, allowing the original hunter to marry safely.{{sfn|Khachapuridze|2015|p=119}}

Even death did not end Dali's obsessive behavior toward her beloved hunters. She would come down from the mountains into villages to grieve dramatically over the bodies of hunters, even those whose deaths she was responsible for in the first place. Some villages had family members stand guard over freshly buried bodies to prevent Dali from unearthing them to weep over.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=66}} In others, the family would leave the hunter's body alone in the house, enabling Dali to dress the body and mourn over it for a short time.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}}

Although not specifically regarded as a [[List of fertility deities|fertility goddess]], two major myths depict Dali giving birth. In one, the goddess drops her infant after the birth. It is rescued by a hunter, to whom she offers a sexual liaison as a reward.{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=33. Dali is Giving Birth in the Crags}} In the second, Dali seduces a hunter, becomes pregnant, and gives birth to a [[demigod]] son who becomes a [[hero]].{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=33. Dali is Giving Birth in the Crags}}

=== Times of transition ===
[[File:Venus-pacific-levelled.jpg|thumb|The planet [[Venus]], sometimes referred to as the morning star]]
Although she is primarily a [[List of hunting deities|hunting deity]], Dali has strong associations with symbols and states of transition, such as dawn, the [[Venus|morning star]], and [[New Year's Eve]]. Svan hunting lore placed significant emphasis on the morning star. Svan hunters were taught to leave their homes before dawn, and arrive at the hunting grounds by its light.{{Sfn|Bakker|2013|pp=83–84}} Once at the hunting grounds, they would light a small fire and offer a prayer via the morning star to Dali and other hunting deities such as [[Apsat (mythology)|Apsat]]{{efn|name=Apsat|Apsat is the Svan name for this deity. In Ossetian, he is known as Aefsati.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=170}}}} (the god of small game) or St. George (the patron of hunters).{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=3}} In the story of the hunter Betkil, his death at Dali's hands is sometimes set at the moment that the morning star appears in the sky, or moment the night becomes dawn.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=3}}

Dali was also celebrated on New Year's Eve as the bringer of a peaceful transition from the old year to the new.{{Sfn|Bakker|2013|pp=83–84}} During these celebrations, she was referred to with the epithet of ''Dæl Ešxwamiš'', or "Dali of New Year's Eve".{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=4}} Both male and female heads of household would make offerings of special [[bread]] baked from [[Consecration|consecrated]] grain to Dali of New Year's Eve. Georgian [[Ethnology|ethnologist]] [[Vera Bardavelidze]] documented a number of different forms of this sacred bread from various villages based on [[fieldwork]] she conducted in the 1930s.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=4}} Some loaves would be kept until spring, where they would be crumbled and sown into the earth at a planting festival.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=117}}

== Mythology ==
=== Affair with Betkil ===
[[File:Mulakhi_and_Mujali_communities_in_Svaneti_(Bernoville,_1875).JPG|thumb|The villages of Mulakhi and Muzhali dotted with traditional towers c. 1875]]
[[File:Village gebi.jpg|thumb|Mountains surrounding the village of Ghebi]]
The most well-known of Dali's affairs is her dalliance with the legendary hunter [[Betkil]] or Betgil, who falls to his death from a high cliff after betraying Dali's affections.{{sfn|Hunt|2012|p=34. Betkil}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=3}} The story is depicted in the traditional Svan circle dance songs ''Bail Betkil'', ''Betkan Kutsa'' and ''Betkani''.{{sfn|Khardziani|2006|p=205}} These dances were performed in the Racha region of western Georgia each year on the third Sunday following Easter, at the bottom of the cliff where Betkil is believed to have died.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=171}} The exact location is uncertain: Tuite mentions the [[Free Svaneti]] communes of [[Mulakh]] and [[Muzhal]], while folklorist [[Anna Chaudhri]] pinpoints the village of [[Gebi, Georgia|Ghebi]].{{Sfn|Tuite|2004a|p=150}}{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=171}} The annual performance of these dances was linked to a ritual meant to [[Rainmaking (ritual)|summon the rain]].{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2004a|p=150}}

The story begins with Dali selecting and pursuing Betkil. She gives him a token of her favor ("a bead, ring, or charm") and demands that he abstain from the touch of mortal females, including his own wife.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=3}} For a time he is faithful to her, and as a result his hunts are always fruitful. Eventually, he breaks his vow with a mortal woman – most often his wife, but occasionally his sister-in-law – and this woman steals the goddess's love-token. In a rage, Dali transforms herself into a white deer or chamois and lures an unsuspecting Betkil from his village to the top of her mountain. The path closes, crumbles, or melts away behind him, forcing him to continue forward until he reaches the peak.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=158}} There, Dali returns to her human form and angrily confronts Betkil about his betrayal and the loss of her token. The ground beneath Betkil's feet crumbles away entirely and leaves him hanging by one hand and one foot. Dali disappears, leaving Betkil to either jump or fall to his death.{{sfn|Hunt|2012|p=34. Betkil}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=3}} In some versions, prior to his death, Betkil entreats his family to grieve for him in various ways, and laments that his mortal lover allowed him to go out hunting while "impure".{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=201}}{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}}

In some variations of the Betkil story, he is accompanied up the mountain by the supernatural dog [[Q'ursha]].{{efn|name=Qursha|From the Georgian ''Kur-shavi'', meaning "black-eared", also transliterated as Kursha.{{sfn|Hunt|2012|p=44. The Balkh Meadow (''Georgian''), note 22}}}} In this version, Betkil is trapped on the mountain for several days and consequently runs out of food. Eventually Q'ursha insists that Betkil kill and eat him to survive.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}} In some versions he goes through with it. In others, he kills the hound but cannot bring himself to eat him. Finally, in other versions, he sends Q'ursha to his village for help instead.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=171}} The villagers come to Betkil's aid and throw ropes to him, but Dali's mountain grows taller and taller and the ropes cannot reach him. Again, he falls to his death.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}

=== "Dali is Giving Birth on the Crags" ===
{{Quote box
| quote = <poem>'I will offer him the choice of three things:
If he wants it, every day
We will give him a moutain goat;
Or else, then in September
We will make a present of nine ''turs'',
Or else, then he will lie with me.'
'I do not dare to share your bed,
Make me a present of nine ''turs''!'</poem>
| source = "Dali is Giving Birth on the Crags"<br/> in ''Legends of the Caucasus'', 2012{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=33. Dali is Giving Birth in the Crags}}
}}The story of Dali giving birth on the crags has been passed down as a song accompanied by a traditional circle dance, called ''Dælil k'ojas khelghwazhale'' ({{lang-en|Dali is Giving Birth on the Crags}}).{{sfn|Kalandadze-Makharadze|2003|p=341}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2004b|p=44}}{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=33. Dali is Giving Birth in the Crags}} Linguistic analysis corroborated by archaeological findings indicates that the song is of ancient origin.{{sfn|Kalandadze-Makharadze|2003|pp=341–342}}

The song begins with a hunter named Mepsay or Mepisa, who hears the goddess crying out in pain from childbirth. Immediately after giving birth, Dali drops the infant down the mountain, where it is snatched up by a waiting wolf. The hunter shoots the wolf and brings the infant back up the mountain to Dali. She offers the hunter a choice of reward: she will gift him with various game animals, or he can become her lover. He warily declines her offer of sexual favors and asks for success in the hunt. Later, he attempts to shoot an ibex with golden horns, not realizing that it is the goddess herself. His bullet ricochets off the ibex's horns and strikes him down, killing him.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=17}}{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=33. Dali is Giving Birth in the Crags}} In this story, the name of the child's father and the fate of the child are never given.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=4}}  

=== Amirani ===
[[File:Amirani_-_Georgian_Prometheus.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|A statue of Amirani in [[Tbilisi]], Georgia]]
The second of Dali's childbirth stories has more variations, but generally describes the conception and birth of the culture hero [[Amirani]]. In the most prominent version, a hunter finds Dali in the mountains, and she takes him as her lover. After several days together, they are discovered by his angry wife, who cuts off Dali's golden hair or ties her up with it.{{sfn|Chikovani|1974|pp=137–138}}{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=11}} As a result, Dali is forced to abruptly leave the world (in some variations, the cutting of her hair kills her outright).{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|p=121}} If she is killed, her pregnancy is discovered after her death.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|p=121}} If she is simply banished, she announces that she is pregnant before departing. She declares that her child will be a powerful hero, though not as powerful as he would be had he been carried to term.{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=11}} In either case, her lover reluctantly cuts the infant from her womb. In some versions, the infant is premature and must be placed in the stomach of a bull or the womb of a cow (sometimes both) to complete gestation.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=4}} Eventually, he is left beside a spring, where he is found by either the Christian [[God the Father|God]] or St. George, and is [[Baptism|baptized]] with the name Amirani.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=4}} 

In another version of Amirani's birth story, a mortal hunter cuts off Dali's braids while she sleeps and rapes her. She becomes pregnant, and an old hunter named [[Sulkalmakhi]] comes across her. She begs him to cut the infant free, and tells the hunter to name him Amirani and care for him as his own.{{sfn|Kveselava|2002|p=167}}

Although Amirani is generally depicted as Dali's son, there is a story from the [[Guria]] region called "Dali and Amirani" in which Dali, enraged by an unspecified offense, attempts to entrap an adult Amirani.{{sfn|Khidasheli|1982|p=133}}{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=XII. Prometheus Legends}} While wandering the mountains with his dog, Amirani sees a flame and begins to follow it up the cliffs, eventually discovering that the flame is Dali's hair. Dali lures Amirani to the top of the mountain by saying she has been looking for him. His dog warns him of her ill intentions, but Amirani disregards the dog's advice and climbs up to meet her. When he reaches the very top of the mountain, Dali disappears and Amirani finds himself hung from the rocks by her hair. His dog, unable to reach him, convinces a bird to pluck the hair away. Just as the bird frees Amirani, Dali returns and curses the bird and its kind to be weak and useless.{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=35. Dali and Amirani}} This is a variation on the story in which Dali strangles an unnamed hunter at the top of a mountain after he stole a hair to string his bow.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=60}}{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=260}}

=== St. George ===
[[File:Coat of arms of the Democratic Republic of Georgia.svg|thumb|upright=.8|St. George on the former Georgian coat of arms]]
Later Svan mythology depicts Dali in opposition to [[Tetri Giorgi|St. George]], whose primary function is the protection of "men exploiting the world outside their villages for the benefit of the community," such as [[shepherd]]s, [[beekeeping|beekeepers]], and most significantly, hunters.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}} The Svan round dance song ''Monadire Chorla'' ("The Hunter Chorla"), a late variation of the Betkil story, depicts a significant clash between Dali and St. George. In the song, a hunter named Chorla kills more than his share of ibexes, despite knowing this will anger the goddess.{{sfn|Khardziani|2006|p=206}} Dali punishes Chorla for his greed by binding him up on a treacherous cliff. Chorla sends his dog for help, and it returns with St. George, who intervenes for Chorla as a reward for his faith in [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]].{{sfn|Khardziani|2006|p=206}} St. George threatens to pollute or destroy the mountains with storms and landslides unless Dali releases Chorla, which she does. Furthermore, he places Chorla under his protection and declares that he can hunt without limit in the future.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}}

Some versions of this story refer to a group of spirits, collectively referred to as the Dalis, rather than a singular goddess.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}} Tuite found the plural representation similar to the "St Georges" and "St Elijahs" of Ossetic mythology, which were groups of spirits sharing traits of the Christian saints they were named for.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}} In contrast, Virsaladze found the change from singular goddess to coven of spirits to be a confirmation that Dali had been relegated to a secondary role in Svan hunting mythology.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=258}}

=== Associated figures ===
Dali was not the only hunting deity worshipped by the Svans, and she was sometimes depicted working alongside others. [[Georges Charachidzé]], a French-Georgian scholar of Caucasian culture, recorded that Dali worked with three other Svaneti forest gods to assist the Lord of the Bare Mountain, ''[[Ber Shishvlish]]''.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}} These deities were Apsat,{{efn|name=Apsat}} the god of small game, ''[[Cxek'isk angelwez]]'', the Angel of the Forest, who ruled over forest animals like foxes and bears, and St. George,{{efn|name=StGeorge}} who was the patron of wolves and hunters.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1968|p=483}} Mikheil Chikovani believed that this multitude of deities represented a later development of the original [[matriarchy|matriarchal]] myth, in which Dali was the mistress of all beasts. Particularly, he saw ''Ber Shishvlish'' as an unsuccessful replacement for Dali.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=38}} 

Some groups in eastern Georgia viewed Apsat and Dali as siblings who each took a season in turn protecting herds of wild beasts.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}} When Apsat was in charge of the animals, hunters were said to have an easy time making kills, but when Dali took over, she watched the animals closely, making it much harder for the hunters to bring them down.{{sfn|Monaghan|2014|p=297}} The Svaneti circle dance ''Metkhvar Mare'' praises both Dali and Apsat in these roles.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=25}} In some instances, Apsat is represented as Dali's husband or son, or even her father, rather than her sibling.{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=38}}{{sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=257}}

Another Georgian hunting deity, [[Ochopintre]] or Ochopinte, is often mentioned alongside Dali. Some sources report that they worked together to herd and protect animals from hunters.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pp=647–648}}{{sfn|Salia|1983|p=92}} In contrast, Virsaladze reports that the [[Khevsurians|Khevsurian people]] of the [[Khevsureti]] region viewed the male Ochopintre as far more important than Dali, who they treated as a minor figure.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=85}}

Some sources refer to Dali being accompanied by hunting dogs, sometimes specifically the legendary black-eared hunting dog Q'ursha.{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|p=178}}{{Sfn|Davidson|2002|p=18}} However, Q'ursha is not a consistent feature of Dali stories. He is more commonly depicted accompanying male hunters, including her son, Amirani, as well as the hunter Betkil.{{Sfn|Charachidzé|1993|p=261}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=5}}

=== Post-Christianization depiction ===
As [[Christianity]] became more prominent in Georgia, many pagan beliefs were altered or appropriated to fit Christian ideology.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=85}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=128–129}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=182}} Dali's functions as the mistress of the hunt began to be shifted to St. George, as in the story of the hunter Chorla, where St. George overrules Dali's punishment of the greedy huntsman. [[Ethnomusicology|Ethnomusicologist]] [[Maka Khardziani]] identified St. George's victory over Dali in the Chorla story as emblematic of the weakening of pagan beliefs in the face of Christian influence.{{sfn|Khardziani|2006|p=206}} David Hunt suggested that the story in which Dali attempts to strangle Amirani reflects a Christian rejection of the female goddess, who is reduced to a malicious and "witch-like" figure.{{Sfn|Hunt|2012|p=VI. Hunting}}

[[File:Francisco de Goya y Lucientes - Witches' Sabbath (The Great He-Goat) crop.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|Detail of [[Witches' Sabbath (The Great He-Goat)|''Witches' Sabbath'']], a 19th-century painting by [[Francisco Goya]] that depicts Satan in the form of a goat]]
Dali's loss of status and power in the Christian era was reflected in altered folk practices. Prayers and sacrifices once offered to Dali were instead offered to St. George.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=84}} In the village of [[Tskheta]] in historic [[Lechkhumi]] province, hunters who encountered "the forest woman" could dismiss her simply by speaking St. George's name, confirming his power over her.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=123}} 

As St. George began to eclipse Dali, she became increasingly associated with evil spirits and demonic imagery.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=132–131}} Her character became entwined with a kind of evil spirit called the ''[[al (folklore)|ali]]''. The ''ali'' retained Dali's connection with hunters and high crags, but her supernatural beauty, particularly her radiant hair, was inverted into horrifying ugliness. A spell to protect travelers from the ''ali'' described her as having misplaced features, backwards limbs, a terrible visage, and "ghastly hair, soiled with blood".{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=120}} Her malicious aspects were emphasized and her patronage and protection of hunters were downplayed.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=119}} Dali's favored animals, such as the wild goats and chamois she often transformed into, were used in Christian imagery to depict [[Satan]], an evil entity who opposes the Christian God.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=84}} This degraded version of Dali is sometimes depicted in the company of [[devil]]s.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=121}} Virsaladze and Hunt have both suggested these changes to the Dali myth are a direct consequence of the Christian church altering existing pagan beliefs to associate them with evil in an effort to discredit them.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=84}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=119}} According to Virsaladze, this was not entirely successful, and belief in Dali persisted alongside Christianity, particularly in remote mountainous regions where the Christian church had less influencce.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=121}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=133}} One elderly man that she interviewed during her research in the mid twentieth-century described Dali as both a deity and as a tormenting spirit, indicating that both versions of the myth were still extant in the modern era.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=119}}

== Mythological parallels ==
More than one author has discussed significant parallels between Dali and other mythological figures from other cultures with similar roles and associations. Equivalent figures to Dali appear in the mythologies of many Caucasian groups. Scholarly comparisons to various figures from [[Greek mythology]] are also prevalent, and some have argued that these similarities are indicative of contact between the peoples of [[Ancient Greece]] and [[Ancient Georgia]].{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=2}} It has been suggested that the [[Proto-Indo-European religion|Proto-Indo-European]] dawn goddess [[Ausos]] is a possible ancestor of Dali, thereby relating her to several similar goddesses descended from Hausos.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=16}} Other authors have suggested that Dali represents a preserved version of a particular Western European mythological archetype of a mistress of hunting or beasts, which has become altered or corrupted in other places.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}}{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=89}}

=== Caucasian equivalents ===
[[File:Historical Svaneti in modern international borders of Georgia.svg|thumb|Historical Svaneti region overlaid on the modern international borders of Georgia]]
[[File:Афсати.jpg|thumb|Statue of the male hunting deity Æfsati in the Ossetian mountains]]
Dali was most important to the Svan, to the point of being their most prominent deity.{{Sfn|Tuite|2004b|p=121}} Other Caucasian peoples had myths that described significantly similar deities who may be considered roughly equivalent with Dali, with regional variations. The Mingrelian people of the [[Samegrelo]] region of Georgia revered a golden-haired goddess of the hunt called Tkashi-Mapa,{{efn|name=Tkashi|Also transliterated as T'qashi Map'a.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=169}}}} who scholars view as an equivalent of Dali due to the overlap in their mythological roles and associations.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pp=647–648}}{{sfn|Khachapuridze|2015|p=117}} Both lived in the wilderness, shape-shifted into animals, took mortal lovers, and were dangerously jealous.{{sfn|Khachapuridze|2015|p=118}} Tuite, drawing on Chikovani's work in 1972, has proposed that the golden-haired goddess [[Samdzimari]] ("necklace-wearer") from northeastern Georgia served a similar, even equivalent role to Dali, though she was not explicitly a hunting deity.{{sfn|Tuite|2004b|p=129}}{{sfn|Tuite|2006|p=10}} Samdzimari and Dali were both seductive figures associated with domestic functions who moved in inaccessible or non-civilized spaces. Each serves as the female counterpart of their respective regional version of St. George.{{sfn|Tuite|2006|p=10}}

Caucasian cultures that worshipped a male hunting deity often had stories about a figure who served Dali's function as the "mistress of the beasts", but was not considered a deity.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=36}} In many places this figure is known only as the "forest woman" or a similar descriptive title. Virsaladze regarded this figure as essentially the same as Dali.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=264}} The Khevsurians, who worshipped the male Ochopintre, retained the concept of a tiny protectress of the cliffs.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=36}} The Ossetians, whose primary hunting deity was [[Apsat (mythology)|Æfsati]],{{efn|name=Apsat}} had a forest woman.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=167}} The Northern Caucasian [[Kumyks]] and the inhabitants of the Lechkhumi and Guria regions each had a forest woman rather than a strong tradition of a hunting goddess.{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|pp=162–163}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=60}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=123}} The [[Avars (Caucasus)|Avar people]] of the [[Northern Caucasus]] have stories about a "Forest Beauty" with golden hair like Dali.{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|pp=169}} The recurring concept of a "forest woman" (or less frequently a "forest man") has been proposed as possible evidence of a common pan-Caucasian mythology that might have existed before Christianity and [[Islam]] came to the Caucasus.{{Sfn|Chirikba|2015|pp=181–182}}

The "forest woman" is a recurring motif in the [[Nart saga]], a loose collection of stories from the Northern Caucasus which underpins much of the mythology of the area.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=123}} The [[Digor people|Digor]], an Ossetian subgroup, have a story from about a deer-herding witch who bears some similarities to Dali.{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=174}} Like Dali, she favors a white doe and uses her hair to bind hunters who offend her, although unlike most Dali stories, the hunters overcome the witch in the end.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=155}} Other Nart saga stories involve goddesses or magical women who, like Dali, transform into deer, have glowing skin, and take hunters as lovers.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=110}} Tuite has also noted that [[Dzerassae]], a water spirit of the Nart saga, had similarities to Dali: she had golden hair and could change her shape into a fish or a deer. He noted that there might be a link between their names based on the initial syllable, with the shift in [[phoneme]] caused by translation into [[Circassian languages|Circassian]].{{Sfn|Tuite|2007|p=27}}

=== Greek mythology ===
[[File:Circe Gumery cour Carree Louvre.jpg|thumb|upright=.7|''Circe'' (1860), by [[Charles Gumery]].]]
Tuite compared Dali in her role as the mother of Amirani to the Greek [[Nereid]] [[Thetis]], mother of [[Achilles]]. Each goddess took a mortal for a lover and bore a [[demi-god]] son. Their sons were destined to be warriors of enormous power, possibly enough to challenge the [[creator deity]] of their respective mythologies. Although extremely formidable, neither attains his full potential, and both are eventually defeated.{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=11}} Tuite posits that the similarity between the two myths is indicative of prehistoric contact between the ancient Greek and Caucasian peoples.{{sfn|Tuite|1997|p=2}}

Classical scholar [[Egbert Bakker]] discussed Dali as a parallel to the Greek witch-goddess [[Circe]] of [[Homer|Homer's]] ''[[Odyssey]]'', highlighting their shared aspects: "protection of animals, sexual predation, dawn and New Year associations," and a "male divine counterpart and adversary." He went on to suggest that their similarities indicated a cultural exchange between the Georgians and the Greeks, noting that the Svan homeland is close to the ancient Georgian kingdom of [[Colchis]], a region with close trading connections to Greece.{{sfn|Bakker|2013|p=84}} 

Some sources have noted a similarity to the Greek goddess [[Artemis]], who was also a patron of wild animals and hunting, although unlike Dali she was known for prudishness rather than promiscuity.{{Sfn|Camuri|1993|p=123}}{{sfn|Horn|1998|p=249}}{{Sfn|Davidson|2002|p=152}} Both were associated with transitions and boundaries, especially between civilization and the wilderness.{{Sfn|Davidson|2002|p=18}}{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|pp=15–19}}

=== Indo-European goddesses ===
[[File:Naked woman holding her breasts-Sb 7742-IMG 0880-black.jpg|thumb|upright=.7|Statuette of woman clutching her breasts, possibly representing Ishtar, from [[Susa]] ({{circa}} 1300 – {{circa}} 1100 BC){{sfn|Pumpelly|1908|p=48}}|alt=]]
Writing in the 1940s, the Georgian author [[Demna Shengelaya]] examined Dali as an equivalent of the [[Babylonian religion|Babylonian]] goddess [[Ishtar]], identifying themes of matriarchy struggling against patriarchal values reflected in the stories of each.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=26}} 

Virsaladze found similarities between Dali and several related deities including Ishtar, the [[Phrygia|Phrygia]]n goddess [[Cybele]], [[Phoenicia]]n [[Astarte]], and [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] [[Tanit]], noting that all of these goddesses were associated with a mortal lover in a story cycle that represented the transition to spring and the cyclical rebirth of nature.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=101}} She particularly stressed the similarities between Dali and Ishtar: sovereignty over animals, an association with dawn, and a sexual aggressiveness that was feared by men.{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=111}}{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=114}} She suggested the possibility that the mythology surrounding Dali represented a preserved form of "a very ancient cycle of traditions and songs about the interrelations of the mistress, patroness, or sovereign, of the beasts, forest, crags and waters, with a mortal young man."{{Sfn|Virsaladze|2017|p=115}} According to Virsaladze, this mythological motif is a fragment of a matriarchal belief system which venerated nature and life-giving mother deities, later supplanted by patriarchal ideology.{{Sfn|Tuite|2004b|p=14}}

Drawing on the work of earlier writers such as Walter Burkert and Paul Friedrich, Tuite described mythological similarities between Dali and several other similar goddesses possibly descended from the Proto-Indo-European Ausos, such as the Greek goddesses [[Aphrodite]] and [[Eos]], the [[Sumerian religion|Sumerian]] [[Inanna]], and the Babylonian Ishtar.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|pp=15–16}} Foremost among these similarities are an association with gold (both as a [[Gold (color)|color]] and as a [[precious metal]]), fertility and patronage of animals, seductive behavior combined with destructive jealousy, and a connection to dawn or the morning star.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|pp=15–19}} All together, he refers to these similarities as the "[[dawn goddess]] complex".{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|p=16}} Tuite identifies the overarching theme of the dawn goddess complex as ambiguity and transition. He notes that the mythological associations of these goddesses serve as symbols for larger concepts such as transitions between night to day, old to new, and birth to death. In Dali's case, her identification with both the morning star and [[New Year's Eve]] directly reinforce her status as a patron of transitions.{{Sfn|Tuite|2006|pp=18–19}}

=== Western European figures ===
[[File:DomenichinounicornPalFarnese.jpg|thumb|''The gentle and pensive maiden has the power to tame the unicorn,'' fresco, probably by [[Domenico Zampieri]], c. 1602 ([[Palazzo Farnese, Rome]])]]
David Hunt compared the hunting mythology surrounding Dali to the [[western Europe]]an concept of the [[unicorn]] and the lady who tames it. He noted that stories of the unicorn typically focus on hunting, often in high mountains. Traditional descriptions of the unicorn include features which are characteristic of goats and deer, such as [[cloven hoof|cloven hooves]]. In turn, hoofed animals are important prey for the hunters of the Caucasian mountains and feature heavily in their mythology. Dali's favored animals were marked in ways that make them similar to the unicorn; in particular, they were often pure white or single-horned. Finally, he found a parallel between the motif of a lady taming the unicorn and the recurring idea of a goddess or supernatural mistress who protects wild game animals.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=75}} Although he admitted that the evidence was "circumstantial and sparse," he suggested that the unicorn story originated from ancient European hunting mythology, which he believes was preserved in the mythology of the Caucasus after fading elsewhere.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=89}}

[[Hilda Ellis Davidson]] and Anna Chaudhri found similarities between stories of Dali and the ''[[glaistig]]'' of the [[Scottish Highlands]]. The ''glaistig'' was commonly described as a [[hag]] who lived high in the mountains and protected hoofed game animals. Like Dali, the ''glaistig'' could be both helpful and malicious, depending on the story in question. Although protective of her animals, in some stories the ''glaistig'' would allow them to be hunted, as long as the hunters were respectful and left appropriate offerings to her.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=151}} In other stories, the ''glaistig'' would pose as an old woman and prey on hunters staying in mountain huts called [[bothy|bothies]].{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|pp=151–152}} Both Dali and the ''glaistig'' use their supernaturally-strong hair as bindings; Dali binds hunters directly, while the ''glaistig'' binds hunting dogs in order to leave her free to attack their masters.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=159}}{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=153}} 

Davidson and Chaudhri concluded that Dali and the ''glaistig'' each represent a local version of an archetypal figure of a female guardian of the wilderness, which they suggested is a wide-spread mythological theme.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=154}}{{Sfn|Chaudhri|2002|p=176}} Dali represents a preserved form of the myth, where the goddess retains her power and her beauty. In contrast, the ''glaistig'' represents an altered form, where the goddess has been reduced to an ugly hag and is accorded significantly less respect.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}} They argue that similar figures who ranging from seductive to disturbing were once widespread across various European places and cultures, referencing the forest women of [[Scandinavia]], Greek Artemis, and the [[Irish mythology|Irish]] ''[[Cailleach]]''. The later forms where the guardian figure is ugly or wicked represent a version that became prominent after respect for the earlier goddess figures had withered.{{sfn|Davidson|Chaudhri|1993|p=160}}

== Modern legacy ==
[[File:Dali Chasm of Venus.jpg|thumb|Perspective view of Dali Chasma and Latona Corona on Venus.]]
Dali has retained cultural significance among Georgians into the modern day, particularly in more rural areas where hunting is still practiced as a profession. A survey conducted in 2013 found that, while most people who were either younger or more educated considered Dali to be mythological, many elderly hunters still thought of Dali as a real figure. They recounted stories to the researchers of hunters they knew who had encountered Dali and been injured or driven mad as a result.{{sfn|Khachapuridze|2015|pp=118–119}}

In the modern era, [[eponym]]s and [[literary allusion]]s to Dali indicate the persistence of her narrative in the cultural memory. The [[Dali Chasma]] and the [[Tkashi-mapa Chasma]] on [[Venus]] are named for Dali and her Mingrelian equivalent Tkashi-Mapa.<ref name="IAU-Dali">{{cite web|title=Dali Chasma|url=https://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/1390|website=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature|publisher=International Astronomical Union Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature|accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref name="IAU-Tkashi">{{cite web|title=Tkashi-mapa Chasma|url= https://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/6040|website=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature|publisher=International Astronomical Union Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature|accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref> ''[[Capra dalii]]'', a fossil species of goat discovered in Georgia, is named for Dali.{{sfn|Bukhsianidze|Vekua|2006|p=160}} Fragments of ''C. dalii'' fossils were first located at the [[Dmanisi]] archaeological site in 2006, and are believed to be related to the [[west Caucasian tur]], ''capra caucasica''.{{sfn|Bukhsianidze|Vekua|2006|p=159}} The Georgian author [[Grigol Robakidze]] integrated Dali into his 1932 German-language novel ''Megi - Ein georgisches Mädchen'' in the form of the character Ivlite. He stated that he intended the novel to present a realistic woman who embodied the characteristics of the mythical [[Medea]].{{sfn|Bregadze|2011|p=40}} Two poems composed after the accidental death of the famed Svan mountain climber [[Mikheil Khergiani]] in 1969 refer to Dali mourning his loss.{{sfn|Jordania|Kane|1999|p=20}}{{sfn|Jordania|Kane|1999|p=21}}

