{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}
{{Cretaceous}}
The '''Early Cretaceous''' ([[geochronology|geochronological]] name) or the '''Lower Cretaceous''' ([[chronostratigraphy|chronostratigraphic]] name), is the earlier or lower of the two major divisions of the [[Cretaceous]]. It is usually considered to stretch from 146&nbsp;[[Megaannum#SI_prefix_multipliers|Ma]] to 100 Ma.

During this time many new types of [[dinosaur]]s appeared or came into prominence, including [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsians]], [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurids]], [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurids]] and [[coelurosaur]]s, while survivors from the [[Late Jurassic]] continued.

[[Angiosperm]]s (flowering plants) appeared for the first time during the Early Cretaceous.<ref>Sun, G., Q. Ji, D.L. Dilcher, S. Zheng, K.C. Nixon & X. Wang 2002. [http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/296/5569/899?ck=nck&siteid=sci&ijkey=8dZ6zTqF606ps&keytype=ref Archaefructaceae, a New Basal Angiosperm Family]. ''Science'' '''296'''(5569): 899–904.</ref> This time also saw the evolution of the first members of the [[Bird|Neornithes]] (modern birds).<ref name=divergence>{{Cite journal | last1 = Lee | first1 = Michael SY | last2 = Cau | first2 = Andrea | last3 = Naish | first3 = Darren | last4 = Dyke | first4 = Gareth J. | year = May 2014 | title = Morphological Clocks in Paleontology, and a Mid-Cretaceous Origin of Crown Aves | journal = Systematic Biology | publisher = Oxford Journals | doi = 10.1093/sysbio/syt110 | volume=63 |issue=1 | pages=442–449 | pmid=24449041| url = https://academic.oup.com/sysbio/article-pdf/63/3/442/9164850/syt110.pdf }}</ref>

