{{Geochronology-stub}}

[[tr:Erken Kretase]]

The '''East African montane forests''' is a [[montane]] [[tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|tropical moist forest]] [[ecoregion]] of eastern [[Africa]]. The ecoregion comprises several separate areas above 2000 meters in the mountains of [[South Sudan]], [[Uganda]], [[Kenya]], and [[Tanzania]].
==Setting== The East African montane forests extend across a total of {{convert|65,500|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}, in 25 separate enclaves, which range in size from 23,700 to 113 square kilometers. The northernmost enclave is on [[Mount Kinyeti]] in the [[Imatong Mountains]] of Southern Sudan, extending south through [[Mount Moroto]] in eastern Uganda and [[Mount Elgon]] on the Kenya-Uganda border. In Kenya and Tanzania, the ecoregion follows the mountains east and west of the [[Eastern Rift]] and associated volcanoes, including the [[Aberdare Range]], [[Mount Kenya]], [[Mount Kulal]], [[Mount Nyiru]], [[Bukkol]], and the [[Nguruman Escarpment]] in Kenya, and [[Mount Kilimanjaro]], [[Mount Meru]], [[Ngorongoro]], and the Marang forests (Mbulu and Hanang) in northern Tanzania.<ref>{{WWF ecoregion|id=at0108|name=East African montane forests|accessdate=June 25, 2011}}</ref>
==Flora== The ecoregion consists of montane forests, grasslands, and savannas, transitioning to the [[East African montane moorlands]] on the highest peaks. The ecoregion is home to the [[Afromontane]] flora, which occurs in the mountains of eastern Africa, and is distinct from the lowland flora.
