{{short description|Second period of the Paleoproterozoic Era}}
{{Geological period|timeline=off
| image =
|caption = Rhyacian Map in Huronian Glaciation
}}
The '''Rhyacian Period''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|r|aɪ|ˈ|eɪ|s|i|ə|n}}; {{lang-el|ῥύαξ|translit=rhýax}}, meaning "stream of [[lava]]") is the second [[geologic period]] in the [[Paleoproterozoic]] [[era (geology)|Era]] and lasted from {{Period start|Rhyacian}} Mya to {{Period start|Orosirian}} Mya (million years ago).<ref name="geowhen">{{cite web | title=Rhyacian Period | work=GeoWhen Database | url=http://stratigraphy.org/bak/geowhen/stages/Rhyacian.html | accessdate=January 5, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060819001043/http://www.stratigraphy.org/geowhen/stages/Rhyacian.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = August 19, 2006}}</ref> Instead of being based on [[stratigraphy]], these dates are defined [[Absolute dating|chronometrically]].<ref name="ogg">{{cite journal | author=James G. Ogg | title=Status on Divisions of the International Geologic Time Scale | journal=Lethaia | year=2004 | volume=37 | issue= 2| pages=183&ndash;199 | doi=10.1080/00241160410006492 }}</ref>

The [[Bushveld Igneous Complex]] and other similar [[intrusion]]s formed during this period.<ref name="ogg"/>

The [[Huronian glaciation|Huronian]] (Makganyene) global glaciation began at the start of the Rhyacian lasted 100 million years.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.0504878102 |author=Kopp |last2=Kirschvink |first2=JL |last3=Hilburn |first3=IA |last4=Nash |first4=CZ |title=The Paleoproterozoic Snowball: A climate disaster triggered by the evolution of oxygenic photosynthesis |journal=PNAS |volume=102 |issue=32 |pages=11131–6 |date=August 2005 |pmid=16061801 |pmc=1183582 |bibcode=2005PNAS..10211131K|display-authors=etal|url=http://authors.library.caltech.edu/1015/1/KOPpnas05.pdf }}</ref>

The first known [[eukaryotes]] began to evolve in the Rhyacian period. The multicellular [[Francevillian Group Fossil]]s, at 2.1-Gyr are from the Rhyacian period.<ref name="albani">{{cite journal |author1=El Albani, Abderrazak |author2=Bengtson, Stefan |author3=Canfield, Donald E. |author4=Bekker, Andrey |author5=Macchiarelli, Reberto  |title=Large colonial organisms with coordinated growth in oxygenated environments 2.1 Gyr ago |journal=Nature |volume=466 |issue=7302 |pages=100–104 |date=July 2010 |pmid=20596019 |doi=10.1038/nature09166 |url=|bibcode = 2010Natur.466..100A }}</ref>

For the time period from 2250 Ma to 2060 Ma, an alternative period based on stratigraphy rather than chronometry, named either the '''Jatulian''' or the '''Eukaryian''', was suggested in the geological timescale review 2012 edited by Gradstein et al.,<ref name="Gradstein_et_al_2012">{{cite book | title=The Geologic Time Scale 2012 | publisher=Elsevier | author=Gradstein, F.M. et al. (editors) | year=2012 | | volume=1 | pages=361–365 | isbn=978-0-44-459390-0}}</ref> but {{As of|2017|02|lc=y}}, this has not yet been officially adopted by the [[IUGS]]. The term Jatulian is, however, used in the regional stratigraphy of the Paleoproterozoic rocks of [[Fennoscandia]].<ref name="Bingen2015">{{cite journal | url=http://www.geologi.no/images/NJG_articles/NJG_Vol95_No3_4_Art7_Bingen.pdf | title=Geochronology of the Palaeoproterozoic Kautokeino  Greenstone Belt, Finnmark, Norway: Tectonic implications  in a Fennoscandia context | author=Bernard Bingen, Arne Solli, Giulio Viola, Espen Torgersen, Jan Sverre Sandstad, Martin J. Whitehouse, Torkil S. Røhr, Morgan Ganerød, Aziz Nasuti | journal=Norwegian Journal of Geology | year=2015 | volume=95 | pages=365–396 | doi=10.17850/njg95-3-09}}</ref>

