{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox person |name=Tania Aebi |image= |alt= |caption= |birth_date={{birth date and age|1966|10|7}} |birth_place= |other_names= |parents= |spouse= Olivier Berner |known_for=Held the record as the youngest person and first American woman to sail solo [[Circumnavigation|around the world]] (with stops and assistance) |occupation=[[Sailor]], [[writer]] |nationality=American |residence=[[Corinth, Vermont|Corinth]], [[Vermont]]<ref name="vnews.com">{{cite news |title=Illustrated Interview: Tania Aebi, of Corinth |url=https://www.vnews.com/Corinth-resident-Tania-Aebi-talks-about-her-solo-circumnavigation-of-the-world-140110260 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> |website={{URL|http://www.taniaaebi.com}} }}
'''Tania Aebi''' (born October 7, 1966) is an American [[sailor]]. She completed a solo circumnavigation of the globe in a 26-foot sailboat between the ages of 18 and 21, making her the first American woman and the youngest person (at the time) to sail around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://premierespeakers.com/tania_aebi/bio |title=Tania Aebi Bio; Premiere Motivational Speakers Bureau |publisher=Premierespeakers.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref> Despite many challenges, she accomplished her goal and proved to her father that she could complete something.<ref name="vnews.com" />
==Voyage== Aebi did not take much of a sailing background on her voyage. In 1984, when Aebi was sixteen, just before finishing up with an alternative high-school a year early, her father bought a boat in the [[UK]] to sail it back across the [[Atlantic ocean|Atlantic]] to New York. Aebi went with him and in a course of a year they sailed from the UK to Spain, Portugal, Morocco, the Canary Islands, the Carrebian, Bermuda and the whole group of Islands, heading back to New York City and arriving there in 1985. They did so as novices.<ref name="emahomagazine.com“">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi: The eternal high-tide sailor|url=http://www.emahomagazine.com/tania-aebi-the-eternal-high-tide-sailor/|accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref>
During a year-long trip from England to New York City with her father, Aebi learned the basics of sailing.<ref name="dailypress.com“">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi Became Youngest Person To Circumnavigate Globe|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/1993-04-12/features/9304120119_1_maiden-voyage-tania-aebi-virgin-islands|accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref>
In May 1985, before the circumvention, Aebi took a correspondence course in [[celestial navigation]].<ref name="sun-sentinel.com">{{cite news|title=Sea Change Tania Aebi, The First American Woman And Youngest Person To Sail Around The World Alone|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-02-05/features/9101060974_1_tania-aebi-ernst-aebi-voyage|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
Aebi had practically no sailing or navigation experience when she departed on her journey, on 28 May 1985. She was eighteen years old when she departed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cunneff |first=Tom |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20097653,00.html |title=Around the World in 29 Months, Tania Aebi Blows into New York with a Record Guinness May Not Validate |publisher=People.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref> Aebi did not have a [[GPS]] receiver because civilian GPS receivers were unavailable. Instead, Aebi had a [[sextant]] for [[celestial navigation]] and a [[radio direction finder]]. She used the first leg of her trip from New Jersey to Bermuda as a [[sea trial]] of her boat and was plagued by factory defects that may easily have been corrected before departure had they been exposed.<ref name="syacht.de">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebis alte "Varuna" als Geisterschiff auf dem Atlantik|url=https://www.yacht.de/aktuell/panorama/tania-aebis-alte-varuna-als-geisterschiff-auf-dem-atlantik/a113844.html|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
==Reactions== Hearing of Aebi's father's round-the-world offer, many sailors accused Ernst Aebi of taking a cavalier attitude toward his daughter's safety, to which he responded: {{quote|I didn't feel it was irresponsible. It's a lot less risky to be on the ocean than to be hanging out in bars at 4 a.m. on the Lower East Side like she used to do.<ref>{{cite news|title=round the World in 29 Months, Tania Aebi Blows into New York with a Record Guinness May Not Validate |url=https://people.com/archive/around-the-world-in-29-months-tania-aebi-blows-into-new-york-with-a-record-guinness-may-not-validate-vol-28-no-21/ |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>}}
==Boat== [[File:Contessa 26 Nocturne II sailboat 3977.jpg|thumb|Aebi sailed a Taylor 26 when she became the youngest woman to single-handedly circumnavigate the globe.<ref name="sailboatdata.com" />]] Aebi set out on her circumnavigation in her $40,000 sloop, ''Varuna'', on May 28, 1985, her only other sailing experience being a six-month cruise of the Atlantic she had made with her father, her two sisters and her brother.<ref name="boatus.com">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi: First American Woman Circumnavigator|url=https://www.boatus.com/magazine/2016/april/tania-aebi-first-american-woman-circumnavigator.aspl |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> ''Varuna'' was called so after a [[Varuna|Vedic deity]] associated with sky, waters, justice and truth. The boat was a Taylor 26, a Canadian version of [[Contessa 26]],<ref name="sailboatdata.com">{{cite news|title=Contessa 26: Sailboat Data |url=http://sailboatdata.com/viewrecord.asp?class_id=3532 |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> which cost $40,000.<ref name="nytimes1">{{cite news|title=For Tania Aebi, the young solo sailor from New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/07/nyregion/after-circling-globe-home-is-the-sailor.html |accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> Aebi's arrival back in New York City on November 6, 1987, after a cold November, transit across the Atlantic on Varuna was heralded nationally by the news media.<ref name="nytimes.com">{{cite news|title=After Circling Globe, Home Is the Sailor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/06/us/sailor-finishes-global-course-in-growing-up.html |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
Upon Aebi's arrival in New york on Varuna, [[President Reagan]] sent Aebi a message saying: {{quote|You set your energy and youth against an ancient challenge on the ageless seas, and you triumphed.''<ref name="nytimes.com"/>}}
===Global circumnavigation route=== In May 1985, with only few months of limited sailing experience, Aebi sailed away from a [[New York City]] dock, bound for [[Bermuda]] in her small boat.<ref name="publishersweekly.com">{{cite news|title=Challenged by her German-Swiss father, an 18-year-old New York City bicycle messenger in 1988 became the first American woman, and the youngest person, to sail alone around the world.|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-671-66653-8|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> In November 1987 Aebi returned to New York City.<ref name="newspapers.bc.edu">{{cite news|title=Aebi Details Her Solo Sail Around the World|url=https://newspapers.bc.edu/?a=d&d=bcheights19910128.2.67|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
==Sponsorship== Aebi's journey was sponsored in part by ''Cruising World'' magazine, for which she had written articles.<ref name="curtisbrown.co.uk">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi's ''Maiden Voyage'' to be adapted into a film |url=https://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/news/tania-aebis-modern-voyage-to-be-adapted-into-a-film|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
After Aebi's return from her 3 year long voyage, Cruising World magazine commented: {{quote|"When anybody that young departs on an adventure that dangerous and does it successfully, it is an example to us all."<ref name="csmonitor.com">{{cite news|title=Globe-circling sailors pursue the ultimate getaway |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/1105/asail.html|accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref>}}
==Later activities== Tarzoon, the cat who traveled more than half the world around with Aebi, survived for more than 20 years and died peacefully in its sleep just before she was to undertake a new voyage with her two teenage sons in 2008.<ref name="aleriasadventures.blogspot.com">{{cite news|title=Wmenandcruising.com interview|url=https://aleriasadventures.blogspot.com/p/famous-women-sailors.html#TaniaAebi |accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> She and her sons sailed a newly acquired steel monohull across the Caribbean and South Pacific during 2008.<ref name="emahomagazine.com">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi: The Eternal High Tide Sailor|url=http://www.emahomagazine.com/tania-aebi-the-eternal-high-tide-sailor/ |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> Aebi traded off with the boys' father, her ex-husband Olivier Berner, in Papeete, Tahiti. Olivier and his sons continued their cruising passage from there.<ref name="womenandcruising.com">{{cite news|title=Wmenandcruising.com interview|url=http://www.womenandcruising.com/sailing-family-tania-aebi.htm |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
==Notable works== ===As author=== Aebi recounts the story of her solo-circumnavigation in her book ''Maiden Voyage''<ref name="publishersweekly">{{cite news|title=Publish Weekly: Maiden Voyage|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-671-66653-8 |accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> which became a [[bestseller]] in the United States in 1989.<ref name="simonandschuster.com">{{cite news|title=What begins as the sheer desire for adventure turns into a spiritual quest as a young woman comes to terms with her family, her dreams, and her first love.|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Maiden-Voyage/Tania-Aebi/9781476747729 |accessdate=11 August 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> The book is a story of teenage angst, self-discovery and adventure. Aebi's story is unusual because she was by many standards, poorly prepared for her voyage, but prevailed through common sense, skills she both learned and honed underway as well as a strong sense of determination.<ref name="boatingtimesli.com">{{cite news|title=Tania Aebi: ''Maiden Voyage''|url=http://boatingtimesli.com/NY/2012/06/01/maiden-voyage/|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
====Recent work==== In 2005 Aebi published her second book, ''I've Been Around''.<ref name="thenyc.com">{{cite news|title=Guess Who's Coming to Dinner: Tania Aebi|url=http://www.thenyc.com/events/guess-whos-coming-to-dinner-tania-aebi/|accessdate=19 August 2018 |date=27 January 2014}}</ref>
===As editor=== Aebi writes monthly columns for several sailing and cruising magazines.<ref name="discoverboating.com">{{cite news|title="One Mom, Two Teens, No Exit"|url=https://www.discoverboating.com/resources/one-mom-two-teens-no-exit|accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
==In popular culture== In September 2017 it was announced that Aebi's memoir ''Maiden Voyage'' will be adapted into a film, with the working title of ''Girl at Sea''. The adaptation was bought by Cohen Media Group in 2017 with the film script written by screenwriter Joel Silverman.<ref name="deadline.com">{{cite news|title=Cohen Media Group Acquires YA Pitch ‘Girl At Sea'; Teen Sails Around The World |url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/tania-aebi-girl-at-sea-maiden-voyage-cohen-media-group-1201908077 |accessdate=10 August 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref>
